### Area

infinispan

### Describe the bug

When the UserModel is cached via Infinispan it has a lazy list of user attributes.
See `org.keycloak.models.cache.infinispan.UserAdapter` and `org.keycloak.models.cache.infinispan.entities.CachedUser`.

After a user remove this list can not be filled with values anymore, bc the user is already deleted.

When we want to access the user attributes from a `UserModel` sent via `UserRemovedEvent` they are empty.

Caused by: https://github.com/keycloak/keycloak/issues/12167

### Version

KC 23.0.7

### Regression

- [x] The issue is a regression

### Expected behavior

All user attributes are available in the `UserModel` of the `UserRemovedEvent` 

### Actual behavior

In a clustered environment: (not 100% sure)
User attributes are not available in the `UserModel` of the `UserRemovedEvent` 

### How to Reproduce?

1. a clustered environment
2. Add a ProviderEventListener 
3. Listen on UserModel.UserRemovedEvent
4. Try to access the users attributes

```java
public class CustomEventListenerProviderFactory implements EventListenerProviderFactory, ProviderEventListener {

  private Runnable onClose;

  @Override
  public EventListenerProvider create(KeycloakSession session) {
    
    return new SomeProvider();
  }

  @Override
  public void init(Config.Scope scope) {

  }

  @Override
  public void postInit(KeycloakSessionFactory factory) {
    factory.register(this);
    onClose = () -> factory.unregister(this);
  }

  @Override
  public void onEvent(ProviderEvent event) {
    if (event instanceof UserModel.UserRemovedEvent) {
      UserRemovedEvent userRemovedEvent = (UserRemovedEvent) event;
      UserModel user = userRemovedEvent.getUser();
      
	  Map<String, List<String>> attributes = user.getAttributes();
      System.out.println("UserRemovedEventListener " + attributes);   
    }
  }
  
  @Override
  public void close() {
    if (onClose != null) {
      onClose.run();
    }
  }

  @Override
  public String getId() {
    return "customEventListener";
  }
}
```

